HERE'S the nightmare. You've socked away every stray penny in retirement accounts, resisting the temptation to live it up, in order to accumulate a comfy nest egg. Now it's payoff time: Hawaii beckons. But all the aging spendthrifts -- the folks who bought fishing boats instead of mutual funds -- persuade Congress to tax your savings and slash your Social Security checks in order to spread the wealth. A far-fetched prospect in the home of the free and the land of the 401(k)? Don't be so sure. For while the baby boom generation's slowly building retirement crisis could be resolved in a variety of ways, punishing the thrifty will always be a tempting option in a world of too many old people chasing too few condos in the sun.

Relaxed from hours spent fishing, the President of this tiny chain of Western Pacific islands, Haruo I. Remeliik, was dressed in a T-shirt and shorts as he drove home on the night of his assassination. It was just after midnight, June 30, 1985. He pulled up the driveway, parking near a hill dense with tapioca and taro plants. Seconds after he climbed from the driver's seat, a shot rang out from what was described as a .30-caliber assault rifle. President Remeliik tumbled down the slope as four rounds were pumped into his head, neck and left thigh. Word spreads quickly in a place so small that neighbors are often cousins, and within hours the 14,000 people of Palau, an American-administered trust territory southeast of the Philippines, learned that their first elected President had been assassinated.

Summary: Seton Hall's loftier goals melted long ago in the heat of Big East Conference play and under a pile of losses. After the bar was lowered, all that was left were visions of a National Invitation Tournament bid, a record above .500 and the chance to build momentum for the Big East tournament. But even those goals now seem out of reach. As losses go, there are worse ones than the 75-65 beating Seton Hall endured against No. 18 Illinois this afternoon at Continental Arena. It was a nonconference game that few people expected the Pirates to win. But the defeat put Seton Hall (12-13) below .500 for the first time this season, and it was its first game in a brutal five-game stretch that will end the regular season.

With the stroke of a pen, Irene Pauls can change her life forever. Because she is descended from German immigrants, Ms. Pauls is eligible to move to Germany whenever she pleases. The German Government will give her a plane ticket, help in finding a home and a job, and the prospect of a higher living standard than most citizens of this remote and mountainous former Soviet republic could ever imagine.

HERE'S the nightmare. You've socked away every stray penny in retirement accounts, resisting the temptation to live it up, in order to accumulate a comfy nest egg. Now it's payoff time: Hawaii beckons. But all the aging spendthrifts -- the folks who bought fishing boats instead of mutual funds -- persuade Congress to tax your savings and slash your Social Security checks in order to spread the wealth. A far-fetched prospect in the home of the free and the land of the 401(k)? Don't be so sure. For while the baby boom generation's slowly building retirement crisis could be resolved in a variety of ways, punishing the thrifty will always be a tempting option in a world of too many old people chasing too few condos in the sun.

Relaxed from hours spent fishing, the President of this tiny chain of Western Pacific islands, Haruo I. Remeliik, was dressed in a T-shirt and shorts as he drove home on the night of his assassination. It was just after midnight, June 30, 1985. He pulled up the driveway, parking near a hill dense with tapioca and taro plants. Seconds after he climbed from the driver's seat, a shot rang out from what was described as a .30-caliber assault rifle. President Remeliik tumbled down the slope as four rounds were pumped into his head, neck and left thigh. Word spreads quickly in a place so small that neighbors are often cousins, and within hours the 14,000 people of Palau, an American-administered trust territory southeast of the Philippines, learned that their first elected President had been assassinated.
